{{DISPLAYTITLE:<span style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Level 955: "Moving Day"</span>}}
{{Blurbackground|file=Oohhhhhh.jpg}}<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">{{Alt Class|ent=1|env=1|ext=1|no=955}}
{{Underline|ffffff}}
<center>'''Level 955''' is the 956th level of the Backrooms.</center></div>

== <div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Description ==
'''Level 955''', otherwise known as, "'''Moving Day'''," is an expansive, non-Euclidean complex of rooms and hallways resembling a typical house in the process of relocation. Most rooms in the level sport the same features, with cream, mint, or baby blue drywall, popcorn ceilings, small, inconsistently placed lights, and thick carpets. These features may vary depending on the room in question. The level's architecture resembles the early 2000's, but deciding when is difficult since many sections of the level are capable of appearing dated or modern. Level 955 has several room variants, including but not limited to: bedrooms, living rooms, staircase tops and bottoms, corridors, kitchens, offices, garages and indoor gardens. The entire level is engulfed in the stench of wet paint, despite the walls already being dry. The smell is noticeably stronger than it would be in [[The Frontrooms]], and it takes humans roughly an hour to lose sensitivity to the scent. The level is affected by [[Phenomenon 14|Shifting Geometry]], resulting in the level's structure shifting and warping when unobserved. Although, in contrast to other levels, the phenomenon rarely occurs. On the other hand, a similarity between these levels is that Level 955 lacks any rooms that are exactly alike.

Level 955 is only partially furnished, and if there is any furnishing, it usually looks out of place. The furniture can be anything, from sofas, cupboards, stands, footstools, lamps, to ironing boards, washing machines, broken sinks, televisions, and even lawn chairs. These household items also appear to have been placed randomly, paying no mind to design choices or formatting. This can result in paths being blocked off, singular pieces of furniture in the center of rooms, and [[Phenomenon 1-A|no-clipping]]. The furniture is usually non-anomalous, and completely safe to interact with. They can even be used to hide behind if needed. Most rooms in the level have the remainder of their furniture inside of sizable moving boxes.

The moving boxes are very important survival tools in the level. These boxes are commonly filled with useful objects such as [[Object 1|Almond Water]], basic groceries, and tools like knives and [[Object 15|Firesalt]]. Wanderers must loot these boxes for food, as objects rarely spawn outside of these boxes on Level 955. Entities, likewise, also depend on these boxes for sustenance since the level's structure make chasing after wanderers very difficult for hostile life. Moving boxes can range from being the size of a jug of milk, to the size of a small car. 
{{Blurimage|file=Fullyfurnished.jpg|align=right|caption=Another image of Level 955. Note the amount of boxes and unfinished furnishing.|width=235px}}
Level 955 supports its own power grid(s). Every few squared kilometers are powered by a large breaker that can form in any random room variant. The breakers generate their own electricity by unknown means, as opening one up shows a hollow interior with a singular gear laying at the bottom. The gear can be removed and the breaker will still be operational. Flipping the breaker's switch will turn off that sector's power grid, and it cannot be turned back on. Fortunately, due to the level's immense size, stumbling across a sector with the power already turned off is cartographically impossible. 

The level has a wide range of common visual and auditory hallucinations. Hallucinations are most common in the first hour, and the stimulus that causes them is presumably the wet paint smell. Wanderers have reported the following hallucinations the most frequently:   

* Hearing a heavy breath nearby
* Witnessing shadows rapidly moving away from you
* Seeing bugs crawl under the drywall as if it was wallpaper
* Hearing a second set of footsteps behind you
* Visualizing bleeding out of various parts of your body

{{Blurimage|file=Limkit.png|caption=A kitchen found in Level 955.|width=235px}}
These hallucinations dwindle down in frequency the longer wanderers stay within Level 955, but they never seem to stop. M.E.G. agents insist they still see these hallucinations as well as rarer ones every few weeks in the level. Studies have been made to attempt to find out what causes these specific hallucinations more often than others, but nothing of value has been discovered regarding them.

Level 955 has a phenomenon regarding it's thermostats. The level is constantly 17° Celsius (63° Fahrenheit), but if a wanderer interacts with a thermostat, they can manage the entire level's temperature, although only the one who set the temperature will feel it. This means multiple people can feel different temperatures at the same time. These thermostats can even be dangerous because their settings are boundless, resulting in some setting the temperature too high or too low and freezing or burning themselves in the process. However, it has been proven that the change is an illusion and that the level's core temperature doesn't change at all from person to person. This phenomenon has yet to be explained, but all subjects insist that they felt the level's temperature change. Some subjects have even exhibited symptoms of hypothermia or hyperthermia from setting the temperature to a harsh condition. 

== <div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Entities ==
Level 955 is dominated by one species of entity, the [[Entity 62|Aranea Membri]]. The Aranea Membri are notably common on the level, but the structure of the level itself mitigates their threat tremendously. Because of Level 955's lack of liftable ceiling, Aranea Membri cannot nest inside. Instead, they are forced to lie and wait out in the open, leading to wanderers noticing them earlier and effectively getting a head start. During chase, the various twists and turns in the level's structure force them to move slower, and many biological factors lead to them being easy to hide from. Aranea Membri are too large to chase wanderers through doorways, and due to their low intelligence, wanderers have survived by simply hiding in the level's closets or hiding behind furniture or inside of wardrobes. 

Because of the lack of live prey and difficulty in getting to prey during chase, some Aranea Membri, most predominantly the younger ones, seem to have stopped recognizing humans as a food source. Instead, they will stalk the wanderer, but eventually lose interest and scurry away (they also may simply ignore wanderers and continue on). The entity can still be frightened and may attack out of instinct if wanderers make loud noises or sudden movements, so if an Aranea Membri seems to be stalking you, refrain from panicking to avoid startling it. Most Aranea Membri get their sustenance from the moving boxes. As mentioned previously, the moving boxes can be stocked with food, and Aranea Membri pick out the raw meats. While majority of Aranea Membri still prefer to attack wanderers, more and more are becoming less aggressive, and experts say that Level 955 is likely to be devoid of hostile life in the near future.

== Colonies ==
Level 955 has many microcolonies, but the sheer size of the level makes forming an outpost impossible. Wanderers are able to form colonies due to the fact that if a wanderer no-clips into the level in a group, the group will end up noclipping into the same relative area. On top of this, wanderers who no-clip into the level will almost always end up within a kilometer of another wanderer currently in Level 955. Most of these microcolonies are run by M.E.G. affiliates, who explore the level and send back any valuable information regarding Level 955. These microcolonies usually will participate in trading and will give refuge to others who happen to pass them by.

== <div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Addendum ==
The following consists of a small thread of messages sent between Hayden McKellar and Dr. Jeremy Heinz, two high-ranking officials in M.E.G. Hayden McKellar is the leader of one of the largest microcolonies of Level 955, while Dr. Heinz is a researcher in one of the most esteemed research facilities in [[Level 1]]. This regards a recent subversion in the behavior of Entity 62. 
<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">
{{Collapse|initial=<center><big>Open Message</big></center>|final=<center><big>Close Message</big></center>|body=
<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">
''To: Jeremy Heinz''

''From: Hayden McKellar''

''Hey there Dr. Heinz, I hope you are doing well. Our microcolony has exciting and crucial information about Level 955! More specifically the entities! Our colony has managed to partially domesticate an Aranea Membri. We did some diagnostics and it appears to be around two years old. We have named it Robin. Enough with the less important things, moving on.''

''Robin was discovered outside of our base, seemingly waiting for prey, but was incredibly calm and safe when approached. Originally, we were simply going to execute it, but I couldn't bring myself to say the word. We took it in and fed it some of our supplies (we can always get more anyways) and set it free. The next day, it showed up again, and we didn't interact with it at all in hopes that it would go away, but it didn't!''

''With this, a wanderer who was apparently a dog trainer in the Frontrooms took it in and began treating it like a puppy. We all thought it was completely adorable, but we kept an eye on it, you know how chaotic Aranea Membri are... Here and there we saw them. One time, that wanderer walked it on a leash and I nearly died laughing. Anyways, it became the microcolony's little pet, it'd come when it was called, it ate out of our hand, and it even defended us from bigger Aranea Membri. We all love it, but we can't sex it until it's antlers grow or not, which could take months.''

''-Yours, Hayden McKellar''</div>
<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">

''To: Hayden McKellar''

''From: Jeremy Heinz''

''I am glad to hear from you Hayden. Some of us at our discovery H.Q. were getting worried we didn't hear from you. Regardless, this is incredible! The document of Entity 62 may be rewritten and research will thrive (and we may even get new recruits)! One unfortunate thing though. I hate to part you and your best friend, but you really should bring "Robin" to H.Q. in Level 1. We can research it to see what is causing this behavioral shift, or if that thing has some sort of disorder.'' 

''See you soon.''

''-Yours, Jeremy Heinz''</div>
<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">
''To: Dr. Heinz''

''From: Hayden McKellar''

''Dr. Heinz, Robin was sent to you via a group of four volunteers, they should be arriving any time soon. Please give me some directives to tell the group when they get there. I don't want them getting electrocuted on that fence Dr. Joanna put in, or missing something important and getting lost, etc.''

''Sincerely, Hayden McKellar''</div>
<div style="background:#6a8100; color:white; padding:10px;border:2px #d1ff00 double; border-radius:15px; padding:20px;">
''To: Hayden McKellar''

''From: Jeremy Heinz''

''Hey McKellar, you don't have to worry about it, we already rounded up "Robin" and gave him a research cell. Of course, we only got him a few hours ago, so we weren't able to run any specific tests yet, but you weren't kidding about his behavior. That's right, 'him.' His antlers just started to come in, so you must have estimated the age way off. They don't start getting their antlers until they are around four years old.''

''You weren't kidding though, his behavior is astounding. However, it is very hard to contain him. This thing keeps breaking out of its research cell and attempting to roam free, but he hasn't attacked anybody. I don't think he likes anybody here. We will do some brain scans and other behavioral tests and send him your way again. We'll be hasty, he is harboring signs of loneliness. Just know that "Robin" is in good hands. See you soon.''

''Yours, Jeremy Heinz''</div>|num=3}}
</div>

==<div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;"> Entrances & Exits ==
The entrances and exits are ordered by frequency.
=== <div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;">Entrances ===

* Finding an apparent "front door" in [[Level 201]] has a high chance of leading here.
* No-Clipping through a box in [[Level 1]] occasionally leads here.
* Exiting [[Level 26]] while carrying any objects from that level will lead here majority of the time.

===<div style="font-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible; text-shadow: 2px 2px 2px black; color: white;"> Exits ===

* Drawing an image of any level below 100 will take the wanderer to said level.
* Sleeping on a bed in 955 will lead to [[Level 201]].
* Finding an apparent "front door" can lead to [[Level 9]] or [[Level 956]].
* Stepping down to the alleged bottom floor leads to [[The Basement]].
* In contrast, climbing up to the alleged top floor leads to [[The Attic]].
